# Orkestrate Landing Page Redesign — Design Document

## Runlayer Analysis

### What Makes It Work

**1. The Hero Illustration is the Star**
The entire right side (~60% of viewport) is dominated by a **3D isometric wireframe illustration** showing the product's architecture. It's not decorative — it literally *explains what the product does*:
- Central glowing purple node = Runlayer hub
- Floating tool badges (Cursor, VSCode, Claude Code) = IDE integrations
- Enterprise cards (Auditing, Observability, Security) = output capabilities
- Thin isometric grid lines connect everything = the "connects MCPs" value prop

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The hero image does the selling. The headline confirms what your eyes already understood. This is the single most impactful pattern to steal.

**2. Layout: Left Copy / Right Visual**
- Headline + subtitle + CTA occupy the left ~40%
- The illustration fills the right ~60% and bleeds off-screen
- This creates asymmetry and visual tension — far more engaging than centered text

**3. Color & Atmosphere**
| Element | Value |
|---|---|
| Background | Pure black `#000` |
| Text primary | White `#fff` |
| Text secondary | ~`#888` / muted gray |
| Accent | Purple `~#7C5CFC` (the glowing hub) |
| Lines/borders | Very thin, ~`rgba(255,255,255,0.08)` |
| Cards | Dark gray `~#111` with subtle border |

The glow effect on the purple hub creates a focal point. Everything else recedes.

**4. Typography**
- Headline: ~40–48px, medium weight, tight tracking — feels authoritative, not playful
- Subtitle: ~16px, regular weight, gray — supporting role
- Navigation: ~14px, clean and minimal

**5. Full-Page Flow (from scrolling screenshots)**
- Section 1: Hero (full viewport)
- Section 2: Feature blocks with product screenshots in bordered cards
- Section 3: Alternating left/right feature highlights
- Section 4: Integration logos / trust bar
- Section 5: Testimonials / social proof
- Section 6: Final CTA
- Each section has **massive vertical padding** (~120–160px)

